to replace it plan.

13:04.717 --> 13:05.685 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And that is...

13:05.718 --> 13:06.853 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

13:06.886 --> 13:08.554 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: They have got
the repeal
part down.

13:08.588 --> 13:10.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AMY WALTER: The repeal part, not
the replace
part down, which is where all of
the real

13:10.857 --> 13:13.660 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
action, when Lisa talks about
how complicated
it is, the replacing it.

13:13.693 --> 13:17.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I will tell you, just in talking
with voters,
even post-election, and I'm sure
you saw this

13:18.031 --> 13:22.635 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
too during campaign, the
frustration that
voters have about Obamacare,
especially in

13:22.669 --> 13:26.806 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the last week before the
election, when notices
went out that their premiums
were rising,

13:26.839 --> 13:29.542 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is cost, very simply.

13:29.575 --> 13:34.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, for Republicans,
the danger is
that, at the end of the day, if
they repeal

13:34.781 --> 13:40.319 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this and do not replace it with
something
that helps to bring costs down,
that they

13:40.353 --> 13:46.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
